<co-content>
 <p>
  In this (non-graded) activity, you must come up with one Hall of Fame and one Hall of Shame user interface. (Note that these interfaces must not be any that have been discussed in the course videos, quizzes, or assignments.) The goal is to help you develop your powers of observation, to begin noticing examples of good and bad design, and to be able to explain why a design is good or bad.
 </p>
 <p>
  Once you come up with your examples, you will post your results to the
  <a href="https://www.coursera.org/learn/ui-design/discussions/weeks/1">
   class forum
  </a>
  . Specifically, for each interface, you should include an image -- a screenshot or photograph -- of the interface and an explanation of why the interface is Hall of Fame or Shame. What makes it good or bad? Between 50 and 150 words is usually enough for an effective explanation.
 </p>
 <p>
  Several course videos should be helpful for coming up with your examples. The video that introduced the concept of Hall of Fame and Hall of Shame interfaces included several examples, along with explanations of why they were Hall of Fame or Shame. You can return to that lecture to review those examples and our explanations. We also provided a video to introduce this activity, which talked through another pair of examples, the websites for two authors, Suzanne Collins --
  <a href="http://www.suzannecollinsbooks.com/">
   http://www.suzannecollinsbooks.com/
  </a>
  -- and Ann Leckie --
  <a href="http://www.annleckie.com/">
   http://www.annleckie.com/
  </a>
  . You should definitely check out that video before doing this activity.
 </p>
 <p>
  After you have posted your examples to the class forum, you should look at and give feedback on other people’s examples. You should give feedback on at least three Hall of Fame and three Hall of Shame examples. Things to include in your feedback:
 </p>
 <ul bullettype="bullets">
  <li>
   <p>
    Do you agree that this is a Hall of Fame or Hall of Shame interface?
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Did you find the explanation convincing?
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Is there anything you can add to a categorization (Fame or Shame) that you agree with?
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    If you do not agree with a categorization (Fame or Shame), why not? What about the original explanation do you not finding convincing, and why do you think it belongs in the opposite category?
   </p>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p>
  Note that this is not a graded assignment. However, you should engage in this activity to begin to develop the skill of interface design critiquing.
 </p>
 <p>
 </p>
</co-content>
