<co-content>
 <p>
  This is a task and scenario description as part of your training in writing and evaluating such descriptions.  This one is specifically targeted at shopping for and buying a product.
 </p>
 <p>
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   TASK DESCRIPTION
  </strong>
 </p>
 <p>
  Sam is a third-year graduate student in Computer Science.  Sam's friend Pat is about to start interviewing for faculty jobs, and Sam would like to buy Pat a remote control device for presentations as a gift (Pat doesn't have one, and has mentioned that it might be handy).  In particular, Sam would like to keep the price below US $50, wants a device that will work with Windows or Mac (as Pat has both types of laptop), is highly rated, and ideally would buy one with a laser pointer.
 </p>
 <p>
  Sam's task is to use the Amazon product search interface to find the least expensive remote control that meets each of these criteria.
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   SCENARIO
  </strong>
 </p>
 <ol bullettype="numbers">
  <li>
   <p>
    Go to www.amazon.com in a web browser.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    In the main search box, select "All" if not selected, and search for "presentation remote".
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Because Sam wants only high-rated remotes, click on 4-star or &amp; up in the filter list on the left of the screen.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    On the top right, after the words "Sort by", select "Price, low to high."
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    For each product, click on the product name, browse through the product description looking for evidence of working on Mac and Windows, and for a laser pointer.  Scroll down by clicking on the arrow on the bottom right on the browser window.   Take notes on a pad of paper or in a separate window.  Note the product, price, review score, and laser pointer.  Only note products that work on both Mac and Windows.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    When several possible candidates are found, select the one that has the best combination of price, reviews, and features.
   </p>
  </li>
 </ol>
</co-content>
