<co-content>
 <p>
  This is a second training task and scenario.  It is in the domain of smart devices.  Note that the device itself is part of this task (because it is inherent), but the solution should not be.
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   Task
  </strong>
  :
 </p>
 <p>
  It is really annoying to get woken up in the middle of the night by having your watch vibrate because an e-mail message arrived (or worse yet, a Facebook update).  But if you place a smart watch on a hard surface (like the table next you a bed), those vibrations can be loud.  Therefore, set a Pebble watch so that it will not vibrate between the hours of 10pm (22:00) and 6am (06:00).
 </p>
 <p>
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   Scenario
  </strong>
  :
 </p>
 <ol bullettype="numbers">
  <li>
   <p>
    On the watch press the left-side button several times until you reach the home screen (the watchface where addition presses no longer change the display.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Press the right-middle button.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Using the right up-and-down buttons to scroll, and right-middle to select, select Settings, then select Quiet Time.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Set the times as desired.
   </p>
  </li>
 </ol>
 <p>
  <u>
   [Note:  It may help you evaluate this scenario to know that if you select Quiet Time, you get a five-item menu with:
  </u>
 </p>
 <ul bullettype="bullets">
  <li>
   <p>
    Manual (which will say on or off)
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Calendar Aware (which will say enabled or disabled)
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Weekdays (which will say disabled or have a schedule)
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Weekends (which will say disabled or have a schedule)
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Interruptions (which will toggle between Quiet all notifications and Allow Phone Calls)
   </p>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p>
  For your analysis, you should know that there are further options under Weekdays and Weekends to set a window of quiet time.]
 </p>
</co-content>
