<co-content>
 <p>
  This is the third (and last) training task and scenario.  It is targeted at calendar use.
 </p>
 <p>
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   Task Description:
  </strong>
 </p>
 <p>
  Prof. Konstan has a busy schedule, and therefore uses a calendar to manage his time.  He is experienced with the calendar and uses many of the advanced features.  He receives his Spring teaching schedule, which has him listed to teach a class Mondays and Fridays from 9:15 to 10:30 am.  He's suddenly curious how busy he'll be next semester.
 </p>
 <p>
  He should check how many calendar entries he already has in his calendar for next Spring, starting by looking up the dates of Spring Semester at the University's calendar website. Then count the number of calendar entries on those days while also tallying the total number of minutes of scheduled meetings.
 </p>
 <p>
 </p>
 <p>
  <strong>
   Scenario:
  </strong>
  (this one is based on using Google Calendar)
 </p>
 <ol bullettype="numbers">
  <li>
   <p>
    In a web browser, go to onestop.umn.edu/calendars.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Scroll Down to Spring Semester.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Note the start and end dates of the semester.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Now go to calendar.google.com.  Sign in if needed.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Go to the start date listed.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Go into Agenda view.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Count the events from the start date of the semester until the end of the month.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Separately, tally the minutes in those events.
   </p>
  </li>
  <li>
   <p>
    Repeat for each additional month, stopping on the last date of the semester.
   </p>
  </li>
 </ol>
</co-content>
